==Old English==

===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*nimman'', from Indo-European ''*nem-'' ‘take’.

Germanic cognates include Old High German [[neman]] (German [[nehmen]]), Old Saxon [[niman]] (Dutch [[nemen]]), Old Norse [[nema]], Gothic [[𐌽𐌹𐌼𐌰𐌽]].  The IE root was also the source of Old Irish [[nem]] ‘present’, Lettish [[nams]], Greek [[νέμειν]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'nɪman/

===Verb===
'''niman''' (strong verb class IV: '''nimþ''' ‘he takes’; '''nam''' ‘he took’; '''nāmon''' ‘they took’; '''ġenumen''' ‘taken’)
# to [[take]], [[seize]]

===Descendents===
Middle English [[nim]].

